ce:section.ce:para:
The DA concentrations in the range of 0–100 μM are utilized to investigate the sensitivity assay. The fluorescence intensity at 475 nm is recorded as a function of DA concentration (Fig. 4
                        a). It shows that the fluorescence intensity increases with the increase of DA concentration, and it has an excellent linear relationship (R2 = 0.9999) to DA concentration from 10 nM to 20 μM. Using this calibrate line, the limit of detection (LOD) is calculated as low as 1.8 nM (S/N = 3). This achieved LOD value, together with the response time, is compared with those published in the literature (Table 1
                        ). The LOD value and the response time of the current work are the best among the chemical reaction methods [20,37–39], except for the lower LOD of 10 pM [41] and 0.1 nM [42] and shortest response of 3s [43]. However, the methods of [41] and [42] have a response of as long as 30 min while that in Ref. [43] has a LOD of 3 μM. Combining these parameters and taking into account the simplicity, the overall performance of the current method is more advantageous.
